depth

price_usd
category_total
old_price




I think my target variable would be price and see what factors affect the variable price.



My predictor variables would be category, sellable_online, depth, height, width, designer, other_colours and old price.




A database of furniture would’ve been built by Ikea , including detailed attributes such as dimensions, colour, price, old price, previous prices, and designer names. Online availability and links to the product’s online listing were probably recorded by searching up item Id. Previous prices (old_price) were probably in the database itself.



H1: Products designed by more well-known designers or those with unique attributes (e.g., more colors) are priced higher and sell better online.
H2: Larger products (greater depth, width, and height) are priced higher due to material costs and complexity.
H3: Products that have been discounted (old_price vs. price) experience increased online sales compared to full-priced items.






How does the availability of multiple color options affect the price of IKEA items in different categories?
What is the typical price range for different categories of IKEA products?
Is there a correlation between product price and the availability of multiple color options?




This is the first graph that I tried out. I changed category into a factor and then proceeded to drop any values that aren’t there in the data set. I then used gf_density to plot the graph. This gave me a faceted graph, therefor I looked at the density chapter on the website and discovered something called gf_density_ridges, so the next graph I tried to use that.

Ikea <- Ikea %>%
  mutate(category = as.factor(category)) %>% 
    drop_na(price, category, other_colors)


# Create a ridge plot using gf_density()
gf_density(
  ~ price | category, 
  data = Ikea, 
  fill = ~ other_colors,
  color = ~ other_colors,
  adjust = 1, 
  alpha = 0.6 
) +
  scale_x_log10() +  
  labs(
    title = "How much do items in each IKEA category cost?",
    subtitle = "Are they available in other colors?",
    x = "Price (USD)",
    y = ""
  ) 











When I tried to use gf_density_ridges I came across a lot of errors regarding the aesthetics of y, which I honestly wasn’t able to comprehend. With the help of AI-tools i came across something called geom_density_ridges and all my problems went away. I was getting closer to the graph. Now after looking at this graph I realised I had to change the X values to logs of 10.

ikea_data_clean <- Ikea %>%
  mutate(price = as.numeric(price), 
         category = as.factor(category),
         other_colors = as.factor(other_colors)) %>%  
  drop_na(price, category, other_colors)


ggplot(ikea_data_clean, aes(x = price, y = category, fill = other_colors)) +
  geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.3, rel_min_height = 0.005) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 10000)) +  
  labs(
    title = "How much do items in each IKEA category cost?",
    subtitle = "Are they available in other colors?",
    x = "Price (USD)",
    y = "Category"
  ) 

Picking joint bandwidth of 936


Warning: Removed 1161 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
(`stat_density_ridges()`).












I discovered something called breaks here to have the X axis values that I wanted but then it wasn’t still spaced out so I tried the next graph.

ggplot(ikea_data_clean, aes(x = price, y = category, fill = other_colors)) +
  geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.3, rel_min_height = 0.005) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    limits = c(0, 10000),          
    breaks = c(1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000)  
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "How much do items in each IKEA category cost?",
    subtitle = "Are they available in other colors?",
    x = "Price (USD)",
    y = "Category"
  ) 

Picking joint bandwidth of 936


Warning: Removed 1161 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
(`stat_density_ridges()`).












This was the closest I could get to the final graph. Instead of using scale_x_continuous I used something called scale_x_log10 which helped me space out the values visually. One problem I had with this graph is that the values are skewed a little bit to the right side compared to the original graph.

ggplot(ikea_data_clean, aes(x = price, y = category, fill = other_colors)) +
  geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.3, rel_min_height = 0.005) +
  scale_x_log10(  
    limits = c(1, 10000), 
    breaks = c(1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000)  
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "How much do items in each IKEA category cost?",
    subtitle = "Are they available in other colors?",
    x = "Price (USD)",
    y = "Category"
  ) 

Picking joint bandwidth of 0.15


Warning: Removed 1161 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
(`stat_density_ridges()`).













A notable number of items provide options for other colors. Beds with additional color choices typically have a higher average price compared to those without.
Certain categories, such as those with storage options, tend to be priced higher probably due to their added functionality and consumer demand.




This data set actually took me a lot of time to understand and visualize. I did learn a lot with this data set such as density plots and ridges and exploring their functionality. After finishing the first two case studies I realised that the geom function is a lot more easier to use after learning the syntax for it. It throws up a lot less errors and that is very nice :’).

race_start_factor <- race_df %>%
  filter(distance == 0) %>% # Races that actually took place
  mutate(
    start_day_time =
      case_when(
        start_time > hms("02:00:00") &
          start_time <= hms("06:00:00") ~ "early_morning",
        start_time > hms("06:00:01") &
          start_time <= hms("10:00:00") ~ "late_morning",
        start_time > hms("10:00:01") &
          start_time <= hms("14:00:00") ~ "mid_day",
        start_time > hms("14:00:01") &
          start_time <= hms("18:00:00") ~ "afternoon",
        start_time > hms("18:00:01") &
          start_time <= hms("22:00:00") ~ "evening",
        start_time > hms("22:00:01") &
          start_time <= hms("23:59:59") ~ "night",
        start_time >= hms("00:00:00") &
          start_time <= hms("02:00:00") ~ "postmidnight",
        .default = "other"
      )
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    start_day_time =
      as_factor(start_day_time) %>%
        fct_collapse(
          .f = .,
          night = c("night", "postmidnight")
        )
  )

again, Unexpectedly Secondary has a higher math anxiety even though they had a lower overall anxiety score compared to the Primary School students.

These are variables that contain the integer value of how much people in certain age groups spend on each of these variables.

Spending Celebrating
Candy
Flowers
Jewelry
Greeting Cards
Evening Out
Clothing
Gift Cards





After Inspecting the data I can already see that Candy has one of the highest means which means (ha ha pun intended) that generally people spend a lot on candy and the least on Gift Cards. This data could be useful for analyzing spending trends across different age groups.


I think my target variable would be age and comparing different age groups and their choice of gift to spend on.



My predictor variables would be all the Quantitative Data that I have because that determines how much which age groups spends on what.




The likely experiment conducted here is a survey, with participants asked to report their spending habits across multiple categories. This data set could represent responses segmented by age group.


The hypothesis could be that spending patterns across various categories change significantly based on age, with younger groups spending more on fun and social categories, while older groups might spend on traditional or sentimental items.





Primary Question: How does total spending across all categories vary by age group?
Secondary Questions:

Which age groups prioritize spending on specific categories such as candy, jewelry, and flowers?
How does the allocation of spending change with age?
Which categories see the sharpest decline in spending as age increases?
How does spending on sentimental gifts (e.g., Greeting Cards, Flowers) compare to more materialistic gifts (e.g., Jewelry, GiftCards) across different age groups?
Do certain age groups exhibit similar spending patterns across all categories, indicating shared preferences, or are there significant deviations?

Business Question:

Which age groups should businesses target if they want to maximize sales of luxury items (e.g., Jewelry)?


With the stuff we learnt in class I could only get this close to the original graph as possible. I have no clue why gf_line wasn’t working when gf_point was :(.

gifts_age <- gifts_age %>% 
  mutate(Age = factor(Age, levels = c("18-24", "25-34", "35-44", "45-54", "55-64", "65+")))

gf_point(Candy ~ Age, data = gifts_age, color = "red", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) %>%
  gf_line(Candy ~ Age, color = "red", size = 1) %>%
  
  gf_point(Clothing ~ Age, color = "orange", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) %>%
  gf_line(Clothing ~ Age, color = "orange", size = 1) %>%
  
  gf_point(EveningOut ~ Age, color = "green", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) %>%
  gf_line(EveningOut ~ Age, color = "green", size = 1) %>%
  
  gf_point(Flowers ~ Age, color = "blue", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) %>%
  gf_line(Flowers ~ Age, color = "blue", size = 1) %>%
  
  gf_point(GiftCards ~ Age, color = "cyan", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) %>%
  gf_line(GiftCards ~ Age, color = "cyan", size = 1) %>%
  
  gf_point(GreetingCards ~ Age, color = "purple", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) %>%
  gf_line(GreetingCards ~ Age, color = "purple", size = 1) %>%

  gf_line(SpendingCelebrating ~ Age, color = "pink", size = 1) %>%

    title = "Valentine's Day Spending over Age",

Candy: Spending on candy remains the highest across all age groups, although it declines steadily from the 18-24 age group (over $60) to the 65+ group (around $50).
Evening Out: Expenditure on evenings out sees a significant drop as age increases, with younger people (18-24) spending more on this activity compared to older age groups.
Jewelry: Spending on jewelry peaks for younger age groups but gradually declines with age, especially after 35-44, indicating that younger generations tend to invest more in jewelry for Valentine’s Day.
Gift Cards and Greeting Cards: These categories show a more stable trend across all age groups, with minimal fluctuations. The spending remains relatively lower than other categories like Candy or Jewelry.
Spending Celebrating: The general spending for celebrations shows a decline after the age of 35-44, suggesting that younger individuals (under 35) are more likely to spend on celebrations compared to older adults.
Flowers: Spending on flowers remains relatively stable across all age groups, with a slight decline after 55-64 years, though it stays close to the middle of the range across all age groups.
Valentine’s Day spending habits evolve significantly across age groups, with younger individuals (18-34) generally spending more on experiences (like evenings out) and luxury items such as candy and jewelry. As people grow older, the focus shifts towards more affordable or symbolic gifts like greeting cards and gift cards, with lower overall spending on celebrations.




I actually had quite a fun time trying to figure out different research questions and the basic idea of working back. the part that I didn’t like was trying to figure out the code for the graph itself as some parts weren’t working and I couldn’t understand why. Especially gf_line on its own. I surprisingly learnt a lot about the function called pivot_longer which essentially from my understanding creates a variable by bunching up variables together to make another variable with levels. I also learnt quite a bit about geom_line and its much more convenient to write than using gf_line and gf_point.

After Inspecting the data I can already see that Candy has one of the highest means which means (ha ha pun intended) that generally people spend a lot on candy and the least on Gift Cards. This data could be useful for analyzing spending trends across different age groups.


I think my target variable would be age and comparing different age groups and their choice of gift to spend on.



My predictor variables would be all the Quantitative Data that I have because that determines how much which age groups spends on what.




The likely experiment conducted here is a survey, with participants asked to report their spending habits across multiple categories. This data set could represent responses segmented by age group.


The hypothesis could be that spending patterns across various categories change significantly based on age, with younger groups spending more on fun and social categories, while older groups might spend on traditional or sentimental items.





Primary Question: How does total spending across all categories vary by age group?
Secondary Questions:

Which age groups prioritize spending on specific categories such as candy, jewelry, and flowers?
How does the allocation of spending change with age?
Which categories see the sharpest decline in spending as age increases?
How does spending on sentimental gifts (e.g., Greeting Cards, Flowers) compare to more materialistic gifts (e.g., Jewelry, GiftCards) across different age groups?
Do certain age groups exhibit similar spending patterns across all categories, indicating shared preferences, or are there significant deviations?

Business Question:

Which age groups should businesses target if they want to maximize sales of luxury items (e.g., Jewelry)?

  gf_boxplot( (realrinc)~ "Income") %>% # Dummy X-axis "variable"
  gf_labs(
    title = "Plot 1A: Income has a skewed distribution",
    subtitle = "Many outliers on the high side"
  )










Is Realrinc affected by gender?

wages.mody %>%
  gf_boxplot(gender ~ realrinc) %>%
  gf_labs(title = "Plot 2A: Income by Gender")

  gf_boxplot(gender ~ log10(realrinc)) %>%
  gf_labs(title = "Plot 2B: Log(Income) by Gender")

  gf_boxplot(gender ~ realrinc, fill = ~gender) %>%
  gf_refine(scale_x_log10()) %>%
  gf_labs(title = "Plot 2C: Income filled by Gender, log scale")










Insights

Income is a highly skewed distribution
the mediums of male and female are highly varied.
the IQR is Lower for males than females.
there are outliers on both sides meaning that some people make a lots of money and some people make very less money.



Is Realinc affected by educcat?

wages.mody %>%
  gf_boxplot(educcat ~ realrinc) %>%
  gf_labs(title = "Plot 3A: Income by Education Category")









wages.mody %>%
  gf_boxplot(educcat ~ log10(realrinc)) %>%
  gf_labs(title = "Plot 3B: Log(Income) by Education Category")









wages.mody %>%
  gf_boxplot(
    reorder(educcat, realrinc, FUN = median) ~ log(realrinc),
    fill = ~educcat,
    alpha = 0.3
  ) %>%
  gf_labs(title = "Plot 3C: Log(Income) by Education Category, sorted") %>%
  gf_labs(
    x = "Log Income",
    y = "Education Category"
  )









wages.mody %>%
  gf_boxplot(reorder(educcat, realrinc, FUN = median) ~ realrinc,
    fill = ~educcat,
    alpha = 0.5
  ) %>%
  gf_refine(scale_x_log10()) %>%
  gf_labs(
    title = "Plot 3D: Income by Education Category, sorted",
    subtitle = "Log Income"
  ) %>%
  gf_labs(
    x = "Income",
    y = "Education Category"
  )










Insights

many Outliers therefor ppl do make very high or very low income
medians do increase in terms of educcat which means educcat does affect realrinc

title: A3: Grades
text:
The purpose of this experiment is to see whether there is a significant differences in grades between students enrolled in different degree programs at Srishti. We will be evaluating based on the three types of degress which are B.Voc, B.FA, and B.Des.



The sample data for this study was collected from students at Srishti who were available at the time of data gathering. To minimize selection bias, participants were chosen through a coin toss, which determined whether each student would participate in the survey. This sample aims to represent the entire Srishti student population. This data was gathered from 90 individuals, ensuring a balanced sample of 30 B.Voc, 30 B.FA and 30 B.Des students, with an equal number of male and female participants to eliminate potential gender bias. Each student was asked about their grades in their last cycle and which course they took as well.
I believe that if we were to conduct this test again, it would be beneficial to ensure that we have equal samples from each course or maintain an equal ratio compared to the population. This would help eliminate any potential course bias in the data and provide a more accurate representation of the overall population.

ANOVA over here is a method used to compare the average grades of students across different degree programs to see if there are significant differences in their performance. In this case, ANOVA tests the idea that the average grades for all degree programs are the same, considering degree type as a factor influencing grades. Typically, a One-Way ANOVA is used, with grades as the continuous variable and degree as the categorical variable. Key assumptions include that the data points are independent, grades are normally distributed within each degree group, and the variances are similar across groups. The ANOVA results include an F-statistic and a p-value, where a p-value below 0.05 suggests that at least one degree program’s average grade is different from the others.

grades_anova <- aov(Score ~ Degree, data = grades_modified) 
grades_supernova <- supernova::pairwise(grades_anova,
  correction = "Bonferroni",
  alpha = 0.05, # 95% CI calculation
  var_equal = TRUE, 
  plot = TRUE
)

Observations:
The output shows the results of pairwise comparisons of average grades between different degree programs. For example, the comparison between B.Voc and B.Des has a mean difference of -0.173, suggesting that students in B.Voc tend to have lower average grades than those in B.Des. the pooled standard error of 0.201 and the t-value of -0.864 indicate that the difference in means between the two groups is relatively small compared to the variability of the sample means. Given that the t-value is not large enough to reach a critical threshold for significance, this suggests that the difference is not statistically significant. The confidence interval for this difference ranges from -0.607 to 0.261, indicating that the difference is not statistically significant since the interval includes zero. Similar interpretations apply to the other comparisons, showing no significant differences among the degree programs based on the data.

Observations:
Since all p-values are less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis for all three groups, suggesting that the data for these degree programs do not follow a normal distribution. Hence, we should further analyse this sample (Permutation Test).

  gf_density( ~ Score,

              alpha = 0.5,

  gf_facet_grid(~ Degree) %>%

  summarise(variance = var(Score))

1 B.Des     1.74 
2 B.Voc     1.27 
3 B.FA      0.615


Observations:
The B.Des program exhibits the highest variance, with a value of 1.7, while the B.FA program has the lowest variance at 0.6. Given that our data does not follow a normal distribution, I can apply the Fligner-Killeen test to assess the homogeneity of variances among the different groups.

fligner.test(Score ~ Degree, data = grades_modified)%>%
    broom::tidy()

# A tibble: 1 × 4
  statistic p.value parameter method                                          
      <dbl>   <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>                                           
1      2.27   0.321         2 Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity of variances


Observations:
The results of the Fligner-Killeen test indicate that there is no significant difference in variances among the groups (p-value = 0.321309). This suggests that the assumption of homogeneity of variances holds for the data, which is an important consideration for conducting further statistical analyses, such as ANOVA.



Permutation tests are distribution-free, meaning they do not rely on specific assumptions regarding the underlying data distribution, such as normality and homogeneity of variances. This is particularly useful since we have already rejected the assumption of equal variances, as well as normality.
Our goal is to determine whether Grades depend on Degree or if the differences we observe might simply be due to random chance. The F-statistic quantifies the extent of variation between the groups (based on degree levels) relative to the variation within each group.

observed_infer <-
  grades_modified %>%
  specify(Score ~ Degree) %>%
  hypothesise(null = "independence") %>%
  calculate(stat = "F")

title: A3: Grades
text:
The purpose of this experiment is to see whether there is a significant differences in grades between students enrolled in different degree programs at Srishti. We will be evaluating based on the three types of degress which are B.Voc, B.FA, and B.Des.



The sample data for this study was collected from students at Srishti who were available at the time of data gathering. To minimize selection bias, participants were chosen through a coin toss, which determined whether each student would participate in the survey. This sample aims to represent the entire Srishti student population. This data was gathered from 90 individuals, ensuring a balanced sample of 30 B.Voc, 30 B.FA and 30 B.Des students, with an equal number of male and female participants to eliminate potential gender bias. Each student was asked about their grades in their last cycle and which course they took as well.
I believe that if we were to conduct this test again, it would be beneficial to ensure that we have equal samples from each course or maintain an equal ratio compared to the population. This would help eliminate any potential course bias in the data and provide a more accurate representation of the overall population.

ANOVA over here is a method used to compare the average grades of students across different degree programs to see if there are significant differences in their performance. In this case, ANOVA tests the idea that the average grades for all degree programs are the same, considering degree type as a factor influencing grades. Typically, a One-Way ANOVA is used, with grades as the continuous variable and degree as the categorical variable. Key assumptions include that the data points are independent, grades are normally distributed within each degree group, and the variances are similar across groups. The ANOVA results include an F-statistic and a p-value, where a p-value below 0.05 suggests that at least one degree program’s average grade is different from the others.

grades_anova <- aov(Score ~ Degree, data = grades_modified) 
grades_supernova <- supernova::pairwise(grades_anova,
  correction = "Bonferroni",
  alpha = 0.05, # 95% CI calculation
  var_equal = TRUE, 
  plot = TRUE
)

Observations:
The results of the Fligner-Killeen test indicate that there is no significant difference in variances among the groups (p-value = 0.321309). This suggests that the assumption of homogeneity of variances holds for the data, which is an important consideration for conducting further statistical analyses, such as ANOVA.



Permutation tests are distribution-free, meaning they do not rely on specific assumptions regarding the underlying data distribution, such as normality and homogeneity of variances. This is particularly useful since we have already rejected the assumption of equal variances, as well as normality.
Our goal is to determine whether Grades depend on Degree or if the differences we observe might simply be due to random chance. The F-statistic quantifies the extent of variation between the groups (based on degree levels) relative to the variation within each group.

title: A3: Tips
text:
The aim of this experiment is to determine whether there is a significant difference in tipping behavior between individuals who follow a vegetarian diet and those who consume non-vegetarian food.



The sample data for this study was collected from students at MAHE who were available at the time of data gathering. To minimize selection bias, participants were chosen through a coin toss, which determined whether each student would participate in the survey. This sample aims to represent the entire MAHE student population. This data was gathered from 60 individuals, ensuring a balanced sample of 30 vegetarians and 30 non-vegetarians, with an equal number of male and female participants to eliminate potential gender bias. Each student was asked about their dietary preference (vegetarian or non-vegetarian) and shown us their latest Swiggy order to verify the tip amount given to delivery personnel.

The T-test is used to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference between the means of two groups. In this case, it helps us assess whether the difference in average tipping amounts between vegetarians and non-vegetarians is likely due to genuine differences in behavior or simply due to random chance. By applying the T-test, we can determine if the observed difference in means is large enough to support the conclusion that dietary preference (vegetarian or non-vegetarian) influences tipping behavior. In this Test we assume that the data is normal and do it.

mosaic :: t_test(Tip ~ Fp, data = Tip) %>%

Observation:
A p-value of 0.61 indicates that there is a 61% chance that the observed difference in tipping behavior between vegetarians and non-vegetarians could have occurred by random chance. Since this p-value is much higher than the typical significance level of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that there is no statistically significant difference in tipping behavior based on dietary preference in this sample.



The Shapiro-Wilk test is used to assess whether a dataset is normally distributed. In statistical analyses, many tests (like the T-test) assume that the data follows a normal distribution. By applying the Shapiro test, we can check if this assumption holds. If the data is normally distributed, we can confidently proceed with parametric tests like the T-test. If the data does not follow a normal distribution, we might consider using non-parametric tests, such as the Mann-Whitney U test (wilcox test) , to analyze differences between groups.

The Shapiro-Wilk test results for both groups indicate very low p-values (1.661e-07 for vegetarians and 2.747e-06 for non-vegetarians), which are much smaller than the typical significance level of 0.05. This suggests that the tipping data for both vegetarians and non-vegetarians does not follow a normal distribution. Given this, using a parametric test like the T-test may not be appropriate, and a non-parametric alternative, such as the Mann-Whitney U test, could provide a more reliable analysis of the differences between these two groups.



The Wilcoxon rank-sum test is a non-parametric alternative to the T-test, used to assess whether there is a significant difference between the distributions of two independent groups.

The test is used to assess the null hypothesis, which typically states that there is no difference in tipping amounts between vegetarians and non-vegetarians. The basic idea is to repeatedly shuffle or permute the observed tipping data between the two groups and calculate the test statistic for each permutation, creating a distribution of the test statistic under the null hypothesis. By comparing the observed test statistic (calculated from the actual data) to the distribution generated from the permutations, we can determine the p-value. This p-value indicates the probability of observing a difference as extreme as, or more extreme than, the one observed, under the null hypothesis. Permutation tests can be applied to various types of data and statistics, making it a flexible choice for analyzing the tipping behavior in this experiment.

title: A3: Tips
text:
The aim of this experiment is to determine whether there is a significant difference in tipping behavior between individuals who follow a vegetarian diet and those who consume non-vegetarian food.



The sample data for this study was collected from students at MAHE who were available at the time of data gathering. To minimize selection bias, participants were chosen through a coin toss, which determined whether each student would participate in the survey. This sample aims to represent the entire MAHE student population. This data was gathered from 60 individuals, ensuring a balanced sample of 30 vegetarians and 30 non-vegetarians, with an equal number of male and female participants to eliminate potential gender bias. Each student was asked about their dietary preference (vegetarian or non-vegetarian) and shown us their latest Swiggy order to verify the tip amount given to delivery personnel.

Observations :
As shown in the graph, many people leave no tip at all compared to those who do. In the vegetarian group, there is one individual who tipped 100, which may be contributing significantly to the difference in the mean tipping amount.



The T-test is used to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference between the means of two groups. In this case, it helps us assess whether the difference in average tipping amounts between vegetarians and non-vegetarians is likely due to genuine differences in behavior or simply due to random chance. By applying the T-test, we can determine if the observed difference in means is large enough to support the conclusion that dietary preference (vegetarian or non-vegetarian) influences tipping behavior. In this Test we assume that the data is normal and do it.

mosaic :: t_test(Tip ~ Fp, data = Tip) %>% 
broom:: tidy()

# A tibble: 1 × 10
  estimate estimate1 estimate2 statistic p.value parameter conf.low conf.high
     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>     <dbl>
1    -2.33        10      12.3    -0.503   0.617      46.9    -11.7      6.99
# ℹ 2 more variables: method <chr>, alternative <chr>


Observation:
A p-value of 0.61 indicates that there is a 61% chance that the observed difference in tipping behavior between vegetarians and non-vegetarians could have occurred by random chance. Since this p-value is much higher than the typical significance level of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that there is no statistically significant difference in tipping behavior based on dietary preference in this sample.



The Shapiro-Wilk test is used to assess whether a dataset is normally distributed. In statistical analyses, many tests (like the T-test) assume that the data follows a normal distribution. By applying the Shapiro test, we can check if this assumption holds. If the data is normally distributed, we can confidently proceed with parametric tests like the T-test. If the data does not follow a normal distribution, we might consider using non-parametric tests, such as the Mann-Whitney U test (wilcox test) , to analyze differences between groups.

Observations:
The Shapiro-Wilk test results for both groups indicate very low p-values (1.661e-07 for vegetarians and 2.747e-06 for non-vegetarians), which are much smaller than the typical significance level of 0.05. This suggests that the tipping data for both vegetarians and non-vegetarians does not follow a normal distribution. Given this, using a parametric test like the T-test may not be appropriate, and a non-parametric alternative, such as the Mann-Whitney U test, could provide a more reliable analysis of the differences between these two groups.



The Wilcoxon rank-sum test is a non-parametric alternative to the T-test, used to assess whether there is a significant difference between the distributions of two independent groups.

wilcox.test(Tip ~ Fp, data = Tip) %>% 
broom:: tidy()

Warning in wilcox.test.default(x = DATA[[1L]], y = DATA[[2L]], ...): cannot
compute exact p-value with ties


# A tibble: 1 × 4
  statistic p.value method                                           alternative
      <dbl>   <dbl> <chr>                                            <chr>      
1       463   0.833 Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correcti… two.sided  


Observations:
Since the p-value is much greater than the common significance level of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that there is no statistically significant difference in tipping behavior between vegetarians and non-vegetarians in the sample.



The test is used to assess the null hypothesis, which typically states that there is no difference in tipping amounts between vegetarians and non-vegetarians. The basic idea is to repeatedly shuffle or permute the observed tipping data between the two groups and calculate the test statistic for each permutation, creating a distribution of the test statistic under the null hypothesis. By comparing the observed test statistic (calculated from the actual data) to the distribution generated from the permutations, we can determine the p-value. This p-value indicates the probability of observing a difference as extreme as, or more extreme than, the one observed, under the null hypothesis. Permutation tests can be applied to various types of data and statistics, making it a flexible choice for analyzing the tipping behavior in this experiment.

             bins = 25) %>%
  gf_vline(xintercept = obs_diff_gender, 
           colour = "purple", linewidth = 1,
           title = "Null Distribution by Permutation", 
           subtitle = "Histogram") %>% 
  gf_labs(x = "Difference in Means")











prop_TRUE = 0.3538: This suggests that there is a moderate likelihood (35%) that there is no significant difference in tipping behavior males and females. A lower proportion like this might indicate that the data could suggest some level of difference, but it still does not provide strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis without further analysis. observed_diff_gender is something we can generate with permutations with tip and hence there is no significant difference in tipping across food preference.

My target variable would be Ratio of profits and the factors that affect it.



My predictor variables would be the Genre and the distributor.




The research experiment could be conducted by gathering a data set of films released over the last five years. For each movie, data would be extracted on its production budget and box office revenue, as well as other revenue streams like streaming and DVD sales, to calculate the profit ratio. The study would focus on a manageable time frame, grouping the data by distributor and genre to calculate the median profit ratio for each combination. This approach allows for examining the distribution of profit ratios to determine if certain genres or distributors are generally more profitable.




How does Ratio of Profits vary based on Genre?
Which Distributor makes the highest Ratio of Profits?
Which Genre is the most profitable in each distributor?
What is the median profit across distributors?



This is the closest I could get to the original. I learned something new called stat summary here, it can calculate the mean median and mode of the data. This is a sub function in ggplot. Geom also is a function, just like gf and also helps with plotting of the data. I am using the type geom_bar here. coord flip switches the axis.

ggplot(mov, aes(x = genre, y = profit_ratio)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(distributor))+
  stat_summary(fun = "median", geom = "bar") +
  labs(title = "Profits made by film distributors", subtitle = "Ratio of profits to budgets", x = "Genre", y = "Median Profit Ratio")+  
  coord_flip()











Over here I wanted to make the y axis similar to the original graph but could not figure out how to space it out visually. I was able to define what I wanted but it wasn’t mapped to the profits and I couldn’t figure out how to do that.

ggplot(mov, aes(x = genre, y = profit_ratio)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(distributor)) +
  stat_summary(fun = "median", geom = "bar") +
  scale_y_discrete(
    limits =c("0", "1x", "2x", "3x"),
    breaks=c("0", "1x", "2x", "3x")
  ) +
  labs(title = "Profits Made by Film Distributors", 
       subtitle = "Ratio of Profits to Budgets", 
       x = "Genre", 
       y = "Median Profit Ratio") +  
  coord_flip()













Horror and adventure are the most profitable genres across distributors.
Paramount and Universal seem to be the most profitable compared to other distributors.
Drama and Comedy are the least profitable genres across distributors.




This was actually pretty fun to do as I had learnt most of the syntax for ggplot with my previous case studies. It was fun to learn as it wasn’t throwing up as many errors as expected. I learnt stuff like stat_summary and coord flip.

genre
release_date




My target variable would be Ratio of profits and the factors that affect it.



My predictor variables would be the Genre and the distributor.




The research experiment could be conducted by gathering a data set of films released over the last five years. For each movie, data would be extracted on its production budget and box office revenue, as well as other revenue streams like streaming and DVD sales, to calculate the profit ratio. The study would focus on a manageable time frame, grouping the data by distributor and genre to calculate the median profit ratio for each combination. This approach allows for examining the distribution of profit ratios to determine if certain genres or distributors are generally more profitable.




How does Ratio of Profits vary based on Genre?
Which Distributor makes the highest Ratio of Profits?
Which Genre is the most profitable in each distributor?
What is the median profit across distributors?



This is the closest I could get to the original. I learned something new called stat summary here, it can calculate the mean median and mode of the data. This is a sub function in ggplot. Geom also is a function, just like gf and also helps with plotting of the data. I am using the type geom_bar here. coord flip switches the axis.

ggplot(mov, aes(x = genre, y = profit_ratio)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(distributor))+
  stat_summary(fun = "median", geom = "bar") +
  labs(title = "Profits made by film distributors", subtitle = "Ratio of profits to budgets", x = "Genre", y = "Median Profit Ratio")+  
  coord_flip()











Over here I wanted to make the y axis similar to the original graph but could not figure out how to space it out visually. I was able to define what I wanted but it wasn’t mapped to the profits and I couldn’t figure out how to do that.

ggplot(mov, aes(x = genre, y = profit_ratio)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(distributor)) +
  stat_summary(fun = "median", geom = "bar") +
  scale_y_discrete(
    limits =c("0", "1x", "2x", "3x"),
    breaks=c("0", "1x", "2x", "3x")
  ) +
  labs(title = "Profits Made by Film Distributors", 
       subtitle = "Ratio of Profits to Budgets", 
       x = "Genre", 
       y = "Median Profit Ratio") +  
  coord_flip()













Horror and adventure are the most profitable genres across distributors.
Paramount and Universal seem to be the most profitable compared to other distributors.
Drama and Comedy are the least profitable genres across distributors.




This was actually pretty fun to do as I had learnt most of the syntax for ggplot with my previous case studies. It was fun to learn as it wasn’t throwing up as many errors as expected. I learnt stuff like stat_summary and coord flip.
